  <div class="robarts-desc">
    I had the opportunity to participate in a specialized training program focused on spinal navigation and instrumentation. During this hands-on session, I performed screw placements in the lumbar spine region using porcine models (pig spines), which are commonly utilized in surgical research and education due to their close anatomical resemblance to human spinal structures.
    <br><br>
    <strong>Key highlights of the training included:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Gaining practical experience in navigation-assisted spinal procedures</li>
      <li>Understanding the critical importance of precision, accuracy, and safety in screw placement</li>
      <li>Enhancing my knowledge of spinal anatomy and instrumentation techniques</li>
      <li>Strengthening my ability to support surgeons during live surgical procedures</li>
    </ul>
    <br>
    <strong>Anatomical Similarities of Porcine and Human Spines:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Comparable vertebral size, shape, and alignment</li>
      <li>Similar bone density and mechanical properties</li>
      <li>Analogous intervertebral disc structure and biomechanics</li>
      <li>Realistic surgical access and operative approach</li>
    </ul>
    <br>
    This experience has significantly advanced my technical competencies as a Clinical Application Engineer, further equipping me to provide expert intraoperative support, system training, and troubleshooting in complex surgical environments.
    <br><br>
    I remain committed to continuous learning and contributing to the advancement of surgical navigation technologies and patient care.
  </div>
